cs.NA, cs.MS, cs.CE, cs.SE, cs.DC

Reasoning: 

- cs.NA (Numerical Analysis): The paper proposes two composable block solver methodologies to solve the discrete systems that arise from finite element discretizations of the double porosity/permeability (DPP) model. The paper also employs a performance model to demonstrate the scalability of the proposed solvers. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Numerical Analysis sub-category.
- cs.MS (Mathematical Software): The paper utilizes the composable solvers feature available in PETSc and the finite element libraries available under the Firedrake Project to illustrate two different ways by which one can effectively precondition these large systems of equations. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Mathematical Software sub-category.
- cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science): The paper deals with the flow of a single-phase incompressible fluid in a porous medium with two distinct pore-networks and with a possibility of mass transfer between them. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Computational Engineering sub-category.
- cs.SE (Software Engineering): The paper provides sample computer codes to illustrate how one can easily implement the proposed block solver methodologies through PETSc command line options. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Software Engineering sub-category.
